    <section class="guide-body">

      <p>
        For most business owners, selling their business is the largest financial transaction of their
        life — and one they have never done before. A business broker is the advisor who manages the
        process: preparing the business for market, identifying and qualifying buyers, managing
        confidentiality, negotiating terms, and coordinating the diligence and closing process.
        This guide explains what brokers do, what they cost, and how to find one who will represent
        your business well.
      </p>

      <h2>What a Business Broker Does</h2>
      <p>
        A business broker's job spans four phases:
      </p>

      <h3>Phase 1: Preparation and Pricing</h3>
      <p>
        A good broker begins by reviewing your financials, calculating your normalized SDE, and
        establishing a defensible asking price. They will typically prepare a Confidential Information
        Memorandum (CIM) — a 20–40 page document summarizing your business for prospective buyers —
        and will advise on any preparation steps that would increase your sale price or reduce deal risk.
      </p>
      <p>
        Before engaging a broker, run your business through the <a href="/">free valuation calculator</a>
        to understand your baseline multiple and where your adjustment factors (owner involvement, revenue
        trend, customer concentration) stand. A broker who proposes a price significantly different from
        the industry-specific multiple range deserves a detailed explanation.
      </p>

      <h3>Phase 2: Marketing and Buyer Qualification</h3>
      <p>
        Brokers list your business on platforms including BizBuySell, BizQuest, and their own buyer
        databases — using a blind profile that describes the business without identifying it.
        Interested buyers sign NDAs before receiving any identifying information. The broker screens
        buyers for financial capability, relevant experience, and seriousness before facilitating introductions.
      </p>
      <p>
        Confidentiality management is one of the most important broker functions. If your employees,
        competitors, landlord, or key customers learn you are selling before the deal is signed, it can
        destabilize the business at exactly the wrong moment. Experienced brokers have protocols that
        minimize disclosure risk throughout the marketing process.
      </p>

      <h3>Phase 3: Offer, LOI, and Negotiation</h3>
      <p>
        When a buyer submits an offer, it typically takes the form of a Letter of Intent (LOI) —
        a non-binding document that outlines the proposed price, structure (asset vs. stock sale),
        deposit, exclusivity period, and due diligence timeline. Your broker negotiates the LOI terms
        on your behalf.
      </p>
      <p>
        Key LOI terms to evaluate with your broker:
      </p>
      <ul>
        <li>Purchase price and structure (cash at close vs. seller financing vs. earnout)</li>
        <li>Exclusivity period length (typically 30–60 days — longer periods favor the buyer)</li>
        <li>Working capital peg (what level of working capital is included in the sale)</li>
        <li>Non-compete terms (geography, duration, scope)</li>
        <li>Transition assistance required from the seller post-close</li>
      </ul>

      <h3>Phase 4: Due Diligence and Closing</h3>
      <p>
        After LOI signing, the buyer (and their lender, if SBA financing is involved) conducts detailed
        diligence: reviewing 3 years of financials, verifying customer contracts, inspecting equipment,
        confirming lease terms, reviewing employee agreements, and confirming all add-backs to SDE.
        Your broker manages the information flow and protects your interests when buyers raise issues
        or attempt to renegotiate the price.
      </p>
      <p>
        The LOI-to-close phase typically takes 60–120 days. SBA-financed deals often take 90–120 days
        because the lender's process adds time. Cash buyers can move in 30–45 days.
      </p>

      <h2>Broker Fees: What You Will Pay</h2>
      <p>
        Business broker fees are almost always structured as a success fee — paid only if and when
        the deal closes. Standard rates:
      </p>
      <div class="data-table-wrap">
        <table class="data-table">
          <thead>
            <tr>
              <th scope="col">Sale Price Range</th>
              <th scope="col">Typical Broker Commission</th>
            </tr>
          </thead>
          <tbody>
            <tr><td>Under $500,000</td><td>10–12%</td></tr>
            <tr><td>$500,000 – $1,000,000</td><td>8–10%</td></tr>
            <tr><td>$1,000,000 – $3,000,000</td><td>6–8%</td></tr>
            <tr><td>$3,000,000+</td><td>5–6%</td></tr>
          </tbody>
        </table>
      </div>
      <p>
        Some brokers also charge an upfront retainer or listing fee, typically $2,500–$10,000,
        which is credited against the success fee at closing. Retainers are more common for businesses
        requiring significant preparation work. Fees are negotiable, particularly for businesses in the
        $2M+ sale range.
      </p>
      <p>
        Note: if both the buyer and seller are represented by brokers (a buyer's broker is less common
        in Main Street transactions but not rare), the total commission may be split between them.
        Clarify co-brokerage terms before signing a listing agreement.
      </p>

      <h2>How to Find and Evaluate a Broker</h2>
      <p>
        The International Business Brokers Association (IBBA) maintains a directory of certified
        business intermediaries (CBIs) by region. Key evaluation criteria:
      </p>
      <ul>
        <li>
          <strong>Industry experience:</strong> A broker who has sold 20 restaurants is far more
          valuable for a restaurant sale than a generalist. Ask for closed transaction references in
          your specific industry.
        </li>
        <li>
          <strong>Local market knowledge:</strong> Main Street transactions are local. A broker who
          understands your market's buyer pool, lease environment, and typical SBA lenders is worth
          more than a national name with no local presence.
        </li>
        <li>
          <strong>Transaction volume:</strong> Ask how many transactions they closed in the past year.
          A broker closing fewer than 5–8 deals per year may lack the active buyer relationships that
          accelerate a sale.
        </li>
        <li>
          <strong>Listing agreement terms:</strong> Review the exclusivity period (typically 6–12 months),
          the termination clause, and whether any upfront fees are refundable if the broker fails to
          produce a qualified buyer.
        </li>
      </ul>

      <h2>Seller Financing: What Brokers Will Ask You to Consider</h2>
      <p>
        Many brokers will recommend that you offer partial seller financing — typically 10–30% of the
        purchase price, repaid over 3–7 years at 6–8% interest. Seller financing signals confidence in
        your own numbers, expands the buyer pool (buyers who can't qualify for full SBA financing can
        bridge the gap with seller paper), and often commands a slightly higher total price.
      </p>
      <p>
        The risk: if the buyer defaults, you may inherit a business that has declined in their hands.
        Structure seller financing with personal guarantees, life insurance on the buyer, and clear
        default/cure provisions. Your transaction attorney (not the broker) should draft these terms.
      </p>

